channel.title: Crack
channel.description:
A little hash collision job for you. Anyone with a peanut for brain can patch the conditional jump resulting in the correct output, so instead of being a peanutbrain, you are supposed to find a collision in the simple hash algorithm I've put in it. In other words, post a working key combination to pass.
[url=http://koti.mbnet.fi/jass0/Crack.class]http://koti.mbnet.fi/jass0/Crack.class[/url]
It's written in Java assembly, so therefore it cannot be decompiled into Java, and no, it is not obfuscated with a commercial obfuscator afterwards. I hope it'll provide at least a little challenge for everyone. :P

item.dc:creator: @Iamadam Iamadam
item.description:
@Iamadam wrote:

RLN:

Just knowing what the stack is isn’t really going to help, you’ll end up having the final stack value and be like wtf, lol. Try writing the java code for the bytecode as you pick through it, and keep track of the stack as you go.

If you keep track of the stack you can see what’s happening at each stage, making it alot easier to change to ‘pure’ java

item.title: Crack
item.dc:creator: @ownagesbot ownagesbot
item.description:
@ownagesbot wrote:

ldc "hai2u" ["hai2u"]
bipush #20 ["hai2u",20]
newarray T_BYTE  ["hai2u", byte-ref]
swap [byte-ref, "hai2u"]
pop [byte-ref]
dup [byte-ref, byte-ref-dup]
getstatic java.io.InputStream java.lang.System.in [byte-ref, byte-ref-dup, InputStream]
swap [byte-ref, InputStream, byte-ref-dup]
invokevirtual int java.io.InputStream.read(byte[]) [byte-ref, int-read]
dup [byte-ref, int-read, int-read-dup]
istore_0 [byte-ref, int-read] + new local var
iconst_3 [byte-ref, int-read, int-6]
isub [byte-ref, int-(int-read - int-6)]

TAG_1: dup [byte-ref, int-(int-read - int-6), int-(int-read - int-6)-dup]

i got that far, still some more to do, if anyone can help me? I need to know what the stack is after iflt

item.description:
@k00dr wrote:

You need to disassemble the class first, you can use javap for example, which is in the jdk.

[code]
F:\Downloadz>javap -c Crack
public final class Crack extends java.lang.Object{
public static final void main(java.lang.String[]);
Code:
0: ldc #28; //String hai2u
2: bipush 20
4: newarray byte
6: swap
7: pop
8: dup
9: getstatic #14; //Field java/lang/System.in:Ljava/io/InputStream;
12: swap
13: invokevirtual #20; //Method java/io/InputStream.read:([B)I
16: dup
17: istore_0
18: iconst_3
19: isub
20: dup
21: iflt 36
24: dup2
25: baload
26: iload_0
27: iadd
28: iconst_1
29: ishl
30: istore_0
31: iconst_1
32: isub
33: goto 20
36: pop2
37: getstatic #24; //Field java/lang/System.out:Ljava/io/PrintStream;
40: iload_0
41: jsr 48
44: invokevirtual #35; //Method java/io/PrintStream.println:(Ljava/lang/String;)V
47: return
48: astore_0
49: ldc #30; //int 15549426
51: if_icmpne 58
54: ldc #32; //String yep
56: ret 0
58: ldc #37; //String nope
60: goto 56

}[/code]

And then you simply need to understand the meaning of the instructions in order to analyze the code

item.title: Crack
item.dc:creator: @zappacky zappacky
item.description:
@zappacky wrote:

Way to mismanage the stack *props*. However, I like it, despite how exhausted I am:

The mismanagement is only to make it a little more challenging =P.

HINT!!! [b]15549426[/b] is the target hash code and the word must be greater than 2 characters long.

If you didn’t figure that out within 30 seconds of hitting “disassemble”, you dont even stand a chance for this challenge.

A quick note: remember the definition of hash, I just spent the last 12 minutes trying to reverse engineer the answer from the bytecode... hashes lose a bit of info... (another hint lmfao... get it? lose a bit ? << 1! bad joke), so that was just a dumb move on my part LAWL.
More stating the obvious. And they lose much more than a single bit of data =P.
Anyways, hl2 is done downloading, maybe I'll try to make a collision later, for now Gordon Freeman is my master. Plus I don't have a copy of PSBL on this NEW computer; -sigh-

You don’t need PSBL to look at a 500 byte classfile -.-
